According to court documents, the minor’s parent contended the school discriminated the child because of his HIV status.
The boy’s mother said she went to the school to seek admission of their child in class seven. The child sat an interview on December 9, 2015 but he did not perform well and was asked to join class 6.
He was asked by the school to report on January 5, 2016 when schools opened. The school gave the parent school requirements, including the fee structure and uniform.
The parents were to bring the minor’s birth certificate and identification documents on the reporting day.
The parent also told the court that they informed the school about the minor’s health status and at the time said the management had no problem with it.
They asked the school to supply them with softcopies of the school requirements which were sent, but bank details were missing. They promised to pay the fees in four to five days. The parents told the court that they delayed taking the child to school because they had not paid fee.
However, the parents told the court when they enquired again on January 12, 2016 from the school, they were informed the class was full.



